Title: Settling — Silas's Way
Source: V4
Act: II

===

~ Fleur arrives in the capital and does what Silas taught her. It works. Then the first shortcut. The pattern is set.

Fleur enters the capital with nothing but the lantern. She conceals the demon and her abilities. The city runs under the Alderman's machinery — soldiers, banners, wanted posters for witches lining the walls, the approaching coronation everywhere as spectacle designed to cement his divine mandate. The Chosen One prophecy is carved into walls, woven into public ceremony.

She sees people suffering under the Alderman's occupation — the sick untended, the poor ignored, the fearful silent. And she does what Silas taught her. She helps. Not with demon power — with patience. She tends a wound in an alley. She sets a bone for a market worker. She grinds herbs for a mother whose child won't stop coughing. It is slow work, invisible work, and it earns her nothing but the quiet trust of people who have no one else.

This is the honest path. This is Silas's legacy in action. Fleur builds a community — not through spectacle but through presence. She shows up. She does the work. People begin to trust her. She begins to matter, not because of what she can do, but because she keeps coming back.

But the work is slow, and Fleur is afraid. She is a witch in a city that burns witches. Every time she heals someone she risks exposure. The demon whispers from the lantern: let me help. He offers a little power — just enough to make her healing look like mundane skill, to mask the telltale gestures of a trained hand. No one will suspect.

Fleur accepts. The first shortcut. It works. She can help more people, more effectively, with less risk. The demon asks so little in return — a candle here, a hearth there. But the pattern is set. Each time Fleur leans on the demon, the honest work gets smaller and his influence grows.
